  "prompt": "Why do queen ants have wings? How often do queen ants reproduce other queen ants?",
  "response": "Queen ants have wings primarily for the purpose of mating during a specific event known as the nuptial flight. During this flight, winged males and females (queens) leave their respective colonies to mate in the air. After mating, the queen sheds her wings and returns to the ground to establish a new colony. The wings allow queens to disperse and find mates, which helps promote genetic diversity within ant populations.\n\nRegarding reproduction, queen ants can produce numerous offspring over their lifetimes, but they typically do not reproduce other queen ants directly. Instead, a queen usually produces a colony of worker ants. In some species, queens may produce new queens (gynes) during certain times of the year, especially as the colony matures and prepares for new nuptial flights. The specific frequency and circumstances of producing new queens can vary significantly among ant species. Some species can have multiple queens in a single colony (polygyny), while others have a single queen (monogyny). After mating, new queens will eventually leave to start their own colonies, continuing the cycle.",
